'''Mbabane Government Hospital''' is the national hospital in [[Mbabane]] with 500 beds. [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] worked at this hospital at a paedeatric nurse in the 1980s.<ref name="TurokOrford2006">{{cite book|last1=Turok|first1=Karina|last2=Orford|first2=Margie|title=Life and soul: portraits of women who move South Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VCAR_z6hHgUC&pg=PR27|accessdate=21 March 2012|date=10 February 2006|publisher=Juta and Company Ltd|isbn=978-1-77013-043-2|page=27}} </ref>In 2007, the Minister for Health and Social Welfare, [[Njabulo Mabuza]], banned the media from entering the hospital.<ref name="Africa2007">{{cite book|title=So this is democracy?: report on media freedom in Southern Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7f8pAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=21 March 2012|year=2007|publisher=[[Media Institute of Southern Africa]]|isbn=978-99916-62-15-2|page=93}}</ref>
In September 2018 as the government had not paid suppliers the hospital ran out of food for patients.<ref>{{cite news |title=Swaziland: No Food for Hospital Patients As Broke Swaziland Government Leaves Supplier Bills Unpaid |url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201809280147.html |accessdate=25 November 2018 |publisher=All Africa |date=27 September 2018}}</ref>
