{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default--> | synonym = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | specialty = <!-- from Wikidata, can be overwritten --> | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Myopericarditis''' is a combination of both [[myocarditis]] and [[pericarditis]] appearing in a single individual, namely inflammation of both the pericardium and the heart muscle. It can involve the presence of [[Pericardial effusion|fluid in the heart]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Inflammatory Heart Diseases: Causes, Symptoms, and Treatments|first1=Lei|last1=Lu|first2=RongRong|last2=Sun|first3=Min|last3=Liu|first4=Yi|last4=Zheng|first5=Peiying|last5=Zhang|date=1 July 2015|publisher=|journal=[[Cell Biochemistry and Biophysics]]|volume=72|issue=3|pages=851–855|doi=10.1007/s12013-015-0550-7|pmid=25682012}}</ref> Myopericarditis refers primarily to a pericarditis with lesser myocarditis, as opposed to a perimyocarditis, though the two terms are often used interchangeably. Both will be reflected on an [[ECG]]. Myopericarditis usually involves inflammation of the [[pericardium]], or the sac covering the heart.
The [[ACAM2000]] smallpox vaccine has been known to cause myopericarditis in some people.<ref>{{cite journal|title=ACAM2000™: The new smallpox vaccine for United States Strategic National Stockpile|first1=Aysegul|last1=Nalca|first2=Elizabeth E|last2=Zumbrun|date=25 May 2010|publisher=|journal=Drug Design, Development and Therapy|volume=4|pages=71–79|pmid=20531961|pmc=2880337}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00928577|title=Safety Surveillance Cohort Study of Vaccinia Vaccine (ACAM2000®) - Full Text View - ClinicalTrials.gov|publisher=}}</ref>
